## What happened

**.NET 11 removed DSA support on macOS.** Apple dropped the underlying DSA primitives from its security frameworks, and .NET 11 surfaces this — `DSA.Create()` now throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy signatures** (not generate new ones), you have two practical options:

### Option 1 — Platform guard (keep DSA for verification on supported OSes)

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
        "DSA signature verification is not supported on macOS with .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2 — Use a cross-platform crypto library

Bring in **BouncyCastle** (`Portable.BouncyCastle` or `BouncyCastle.Cryptography`) which ships its own DSA implementation independent of the OS:

```csharp
// Works on all platforms including macOS on .NET 11
var dsaParams = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(/* import legacy key */);
var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
signer.Init(false, dsaParams);
signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
```

### Recommendation

Since your library **must verify existing DSA signatures on all three platforms**, Option 2 (BouncyCastle) is the right path — it keeps behavior consistent everywhere without requiring you to re-sign legacy data with a new algorithm.
